# Definition of Done (Frontend)

Before marking work complete:

1. Code matches surrounding style and project conventions
2. TypeScript types are properly defined
3. Loading states are visible and humane
4. Errors are localized and user-safe
5. Mutations show progress at the correct level
6. API contracts are checked against the canonical reference
7. No unrelated refactors or broad formatting changes
8. Performance-sensitive changes avoid increasing bundle size
9. Accessibility requirements are met
10. A short manual validation command is provided

---

# Review Checklist

Reject or revise if:

- The change scans or rewrites unrelated areas
- A full-page blank screen appears while data is loading
- Raw API errors or technical keys are shown to users
- New dependencies are introduced without approval
- Global state is added for local state
- Routing/auth behavior changes unintentionally
- Heavy pages are eagerly imported unnecessarily
- Lazy loading is added to tiny components without reason
- Skeletons are introduced inconsistently with existing UI
- TypeScript any types are used without justification
- Accessibility requirements are ignored

---

# One-Line Summary

> Ship maintainable Next.js applications that follow existing patterns, use proper TypeScript, implement clear loading/error states, optimize for performance, and adhere to accessibility best practices.

